Certain types of customers pose a high risk of money laundering and terrorism financing. We will discuss these types of customers, including both individuals and organisations, over the next few pages.

 

Although it is generally the nature of your relationship with the customer that is most important in assessing risk, you should be careful when dealing with the following customers:

 

Beneficial owners

People who own 25% or more of the corporate customer or control the corporate customer are beneficial owners. In many cases, identifying a beneficial owner will not be necessary because the customer is acting on behalf of himself or herself. You should be careful, however, when dealing with a customer who is acting on behalf of another person, or where the customer is a legal entity such as a company or a trust that involves one or more individuals who could be beneficial owners.

 

Cash-intensive businesses

Cash-intensive businesses include convenience stores, parking garages, laundromats, restaurants, bars and pawn brokers. They may use their accounts to hide illegal cash along with legitimate business earnings. This makes it very difficult to detect the source of their money and determine its legitimacy.
